Two separate issues here:

## 1. `StaticResource` doesn't update at runtime

`StaticResource` resolves **once** at XAML load time. For runtime theme switching, use **`DynamicResource`**:

```xml
<!-- ✗ Won't update -->
<Label TextColor="{StaticResource PrimaryTextColor}" />

<!-- ✓ Updates when the dictionary changes -->
<Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
```

Then swap themes by clearing and merging dictionaries:

```csharp
var mergedDicts = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
mergedDicts.Clear();
mergedDicts.Add(useDark ? new DarkTheme() : new LightTheme());
```

## 2. Android restarts on `uiMode` change

By default, Android **destroys and recreates** the activity when the system UI mode changes. Add `UiMode` to the `ConfigurationChanges` in your `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(
    Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
    ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                         | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                         | ConfigChanges.UiMode       // ← add this
                         | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                         | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This tells Android to deliver the change as an event instead of restarting the activity. You can then detect it and swap your theme:

```csharp
// In App.xaml.cs or a service
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    bool dark = e.RequestedTheme == AppTheme.Dark;
    var merged = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
    merged.Clear();
    merged.Add(dark ? new DarkTheme() : new LightTheme());
};
```

**TL;DR** — `StaticResource` → `DynamicResource` fixes the runtime swap; adding `ConfigChanges.UiMode` fixes the restart.
